
SOC176 - RDP Brute Force (Successful) | EventID: 4625 / 4624 | Critical | CLOSED

Summary
--------
On March 07, 2024, at 11:44 AM UTC, the MSOC Security team received an alert titled "SOC176 – RDP Brute Force Detected." The alert was triggered when the external host with IP address 218.92.0.56 was observed attempting multiple Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP) login connections to the internal host Matthew (IP: 172.16.17.148). The attempts originated from a single external source and involved repeated login failures using different, non-existing accounts. The firewall permitted the traffic, allowing the brute force attempts to reach the host.

Further investigation using OSINT tools confirmed that the source IP (218[.]92[.]0[.]56) is malicious and traced back to China.

Review of Windows Security Event Logs revealed repeated failed login attempts with usernames such as guest, admin, sysadmin, and finally Matthew. The attacker was ultimately successful in logging in after guessing the correct credentials for the Matthew account, establishing an RDP session. I Isolated the compromised host (Matthew – 172.16.17[.]148) from the network, disabled RDP access on the affected system and revoked all active sessions for the account. I directed IT Support to reset Matthew’s account with a strong password, enforce MFA on RDP accounts, restrict RDP to trusted IPs, and I monitored the host for persistence.

